    "Explanation": [
      "In bash, each command in a pipeline runs in a subshell. The `while read` loop is on the right-hand side of the pipe (`find ... | while read ...`), so it executes in a subshell. The `count` variable is incremented inside that subshell, but when the subshell exits after the loop completes, its modified copy of `count` is discarded. The parent shell's `count` variable was never modified and remains 0. A fix would be to use process substitution (`while read file; do ... done \u003c \u003c(find . -name \"*.go\")`) so the loop runs in the current shell, or to use a different approach entirely."
    ],
    "ActualAnswer": [
      "The pipe causes the while loop to run in a subshell, so the incremented count variable is lost when the subshell exits, leaving the parent shell's count at 0."
