{
  "Answer": {
    "Title": "Jenkins agent none Meaning",
    "Explanation": [
      "In a Jenkins Declarative Pipeline, specifying `agent none` at the top level means that no global agent (and therefore no executor) is allocated for the entire pipeline. This delegates the responsibility of agent allocation to each individual stage. Every stage within the pipeline must then specify its own `agent` directive to indicate where it should run.",
      "",
      "This is useful in scenarios where different stages need to run on different agents (e.g., one stage builds on a Linux node, another deploys from a Windows node), or when you want fine-grained control over resource allocation and don't want an executor held for the entire duration of the pipeline.",
      "",
      "The other options are incorrect:",
      "- b) `agent any` or no agent directive would cause it to potentially run on the controller, but `agent none` does not default to the controller.",
      "- c) The pipeline will still run as long as each stage defines its own agent.",
      "- d) No random assignment occurs; it simply defers agent selection to each stage."
