      "",
      "- **b) Error rate exceeding a defined threshold**: This is the standard primary signal. Error rates (e.g., HTTP 5xx responses, application exception rates, failed request ratios) directly measure whether the deployed code is functioning correctly from the end-user's perspective. Tools like AWS CodeDeploy use minimum healthy host thresholds and error rates, Spinnaker's canary analysis focuses heavily on error metrics, and Kubernetes readiness/liveness probes feed into error-based rollback decisions. Error rate is a direct indicator of deployment health and user impact.",
      "",
      "- **c) Deployment duration exceeding 10 minutes**: A timeout on deployment duration is a process safeguard, not an application health metric. It may halt a stuck deployment but doesn't assess whether the deployed code is working correctly.",
