    "Title": "Kubernetes Memory Limit Enforcement Behavior",
    "Explanation": [
      "In Kubernetes, when a container attempts to use more memory than its configured resources.limits.memory setting, the kubelet (the node agent) enforces this hard limit. Memory is considered a compressible resource in Kubernetes, meaning the system cannot allow a container to exceed its memory limit without consequences. When a container tries to allocate more memory than the limit allows, the kernel's Out-Of-Memory (OOM) killer is triggered, which terminates the container process. This results in the container being killed with an OOMKilled status. The key difference between memory and CPU is that CPU is a compressible resource (can be throttled), while memory is non-compressible (cannot be throttled). Therefore, the only enforcement mechanism for memory limits is to kill the offending container. The Pod itself is not automatically rescheduled to a larger node due to this - it depends on the Pod's restart policy. The memory limit is a hard limit, not advisory."
