{
  "Answer": {
    "Title": "Kubernetes Rolling Update Pod Ready Count",
    "Explanation": [
      "In Kubernetes rolling updates with RollingUpdateStrategy, the maxSurge and maxUnavailable parameters control how many pods can be created beyond the desired replicas and how many can be unavailable during the update.",
      "",
      "Given configuration:",
      "- replicas: 6",
      "- maxSurge: 1 (allows 1 extra pod beyond desired count)",
      "- maxUnavailable: 0 (no pods can be unavailable)",
      "",
      "With maxUnavailable: 0, all existing pods must remain available throughout the update. This means no old-version pod can be terminated until its replacement is ready.",
      "",
      "With maxSurge: 1, Kubernetes can create 1 additional pod beyond the desired replica count. So the cluster can have up to 6 (desired) + 1 (surge) = 7 pods total during the update.",
      "",
      "The update process works as follows:",
      "1. Create 1 new-version pod (now: 6 old + 1 new = 7 total)",
      "2. Wait for this new pod to be Ready",
      "3. Once the new pod is Ready, terminate 1 old-version pod",
      "4. Create another new-version pod to replace it",
      "5. Repeat until all replicas are updated",
      "",
      "Therefore, only 1 new-version pod must be Ready before any old-version pod can be terminated. The maxUnavailable: 0 constraint means we must have a ready replacement before removing the old pod, and maxSurge: 1 allows us to create that one replacement pod while keeping all old pods running."
    ],
    "ActualAnswer": [
      "1"
    ],
