    "Title": "Safe Git Undo for Shared Branches",
    "Explanation": [
      "When working with a shared branch that has already been pushed to a remote repository, rewriting history is dangerous because it can cause conflicts for other developers who have already pulled those commits. The question asks for the safe approach that doesn't rewrite history.",
      "",
      "Let's analyze each option:",
      "",
      "a) `git reset --hard HEAD~1` - This command moves the HEAD pointer back one commit and rewrites history by removing the commit from the branch. This is unsafe for shared branches because it changes the commit history that other developers may have already pulled.",
      "",
      "b) `git revert HEAD` - This command creates a NEW commit that undoes the changes introduced by the previous commit. It doesn't rewrite history; instead, it adds a new commit to the history. This is the safe approach for shared branches because all developers can simply pull the new revert commit without any conflicts from history rewriting.",
      "",
      "c) `git checkout HEAD~1` - This command moves to a previous commit in a detached HEAD state. It doesn't undo the commit on the branch and doesn't help in this scenario.",
      "",
      "d) `git stash` - This command temporarily saves uncommitted changes but doesn't undo commits. It's not relevant for this situation.",
      "",
      "The correct answer is `git revert HEAD` because it's the only method that safely undoes a commit without rewriting history. It creates a new commit that reverses the changes, allowing other developers to stay in sync."
    ],
    "ActualAnswer": [
      "b)"
    ],
