    "Explanation": [
      "In Jenkins Declarative Pipeline, the `agent` directive specifies where the pipeline or a specific stage will execute. When `agent none` is specified at the top level of the pipeline, it means that no global agent (executor) is allocated for the entire pipeline. This has an important implication: each stage within the pipeline must define its own `agent` directive to specify where it should run.",
      "",
      "This approach is useful in several scenarios:",
      "1. When different stages need to run on different types of agents (e.g., one stage on Linux, another on Windows)",
      "2. When you want to minimize executor usage by only allocating agents when needed",
      "3. When stages have different resource requirements",
      "",
      "Let's examine why the other options are incorrect:",
