{
  "Answer": {
    "Title": "Bash pipefail Exit Status",
    "Explanation": [
      "The `set -o pipefail` command alters the default behavior for determining a pipeline's exit status. Normally, the exit status of a pipeline is that of the last command. Without `pipefail`, the pipeline `false | true` would have an exit status of 0, because `true` is the last command and it exits with 0. However, when `pipefail` is enabled, the pipeline's exit status is the exit status of the rightmost command that exited with a non-zero status. In the pipeline `false | true`, the `false` command exits with 1 (non-zero), and `true` exits with 0. Since `false` is the rightmost command to fail, the exit status of the entire pipeline becomes 1. The special variable `$?` holds the exit status of the last executed command. Consequently, `echo $?` prints the value 1."
    ],
