      "b) git revert HEAD: This command creates a new commit that undoes the changes introduced by the specified commit (in this case, HEAD, which is the last commit). The original commit remains in the history, and a new 'revert' commit is added. This is the safest way to undo changes on a shared, pushed branch because it does not rewrite history.",
      "c) git checkout HEAD~1: This command moves the HEAD pointer to the commit before the last one, putting the repository into a 'detached HEAD' state. It does not undo the commit on the branch itself; the last commit still exists in the branch's history.",
      "d) git stash: This command temporarily saves uncommitted changes (both staged and unstaged) and reverts the working directory to the HEAD commit. It is used for saving local work, not for undoing committed changes on a branch's history.",
      "",
      "Therefore, 'git revert HEAD' is the appropriate command as it undoes the changes of the last commit by creating a new commit, thus preserving the history."
