    "Explanation": [
      "Terraform reads the remote state, computes a plan, applies changes, and writes an updated state file. If two users run terraform apply at the same time without state locking, both can read the same base state and then both attempt to write updates. Because Terraform does not merge concurrent changes, the later write can overwrite or interleave with the earlier one, causing lost updates or a corrupted/inconsistent state. Backends that support state locking (Terraform Cloud, or S3 + DynamoDB locking, etc.) prevent this; without locking you must coordinate applies."
